strapiArticle.title: Howdy!
strapiArticle.description: Hi - I'm Erik. This is my blog. Where I blog.
strapiArticle.content:
Hi - I'm Erik. This is my blog. Where I blog.

But you know that. That's why you're here.

I either sent you a link or a resume or you've stumbled across the web to this site somehow: My blog.

Hello, I am glad you're here no matter how you got here. :)

I'm Erik. I'm a WordPress writer & developer gone rogue into a JavaScript heavy full-stack engineer. I also do photography, copy-writing, social-media.

Anyways! this is mostly a coding project held together by Strapi.js - a react-node stack-library. I'm hoping to use my knowledge using this tool to make a more robust, interactive system for an open source data base for a D&D:5e compendium/wiki that will eventually be rebranded as general "rpgstories" site with a podcast, user-submitted database of dnd stories, blog, etc. If you're interested - feel free to keep following this blog. It may become a sort of public-journal filled with my own writings, thoughts, and general ramblings. It may have this and like one other post with barely anything in it because it's also hopefully a means through which to demonstrate a working understanding of making a full-stack website/application.

Or it may change into a sorta other thing I have in mind. I'm not sure. I've got a lot of ideas!

Which leads me to why I'm even doing this blog and writing an actual blog rather than inserting dummy data for a resume project: I can write! Yes! And I love to write, it's the reason my chosen career path is in computer programming: I just like to type and as Derrida said: "play with words".

If you're still reading, thank you and - indulge me for a moment:

Play is in words, and play is language. Play is in concepts. Here's Derrida on the concept: "All is textual play with no connection with original truth."

Which sounds a lot heavier than just playing around with words - but that's another, more earnest conversation/potential blog-post. So yeah, you get it: I was an English Major and I like deconstructionist philosophies, especially when it comes to linguistics. So I can write! that's why I'm writing this blog and the only reason I'm not using some horrible laurem ipsum dummy data blog posts for this resume. And with that in mind, know I am simply continuing to write as I want this to look and function as a real blog but also it looks great to have a lot of words in a blog post on a resume project. I don't mean to be an insincere host/narrator/writer, I mean to be honest and not waste your time - everything after this bit is just a bunch of stuff about whatever, I don't even know yet! I'm just free-writing now. So here we go off the rails and into the whole blogging thing:

Which brings me to reasons you might continue reading this blog post an/or following my blog which is me shamelessly promoting work because we all gotta make money:

Yes, you can hire me! Need something written? I've been writing web-copy for years & writing as an English Major for 5 years - we can pen any sentence you wish. If it's advertising, ghost-writing, web copy, academic, blog or article writing I've got you covered. Any ways, when I get the link for my portfolio website I'll include a link to the writing section right here:

Yes, you can hire me to code! Have a website project in mind? Are you a recruiter looking for someone with full-stack experience? I'm looking for work and just graduated the Lambda Programing Full-Stack program. I'm working on a few personal projects at the moment, this blog site and the D&D site included, and if you're another developer and think it sounds like something you'd be interested in working on or submitting to please feel free to email me at: erikaburdet@gmail.com.

Also I think I'm going to make some cool things that might entertain ya! I've got a podcast about dungeons & dragons coming up along with that website I mentioned earlier. If you're into D&D or just RPG games in general - stick around, everyone is welcome.

Anyways... You're still reading?

Alright, maybe I'll write something interesting in a follow up post as a thank you for reading. But at the moment I'm just impressed that you're still reading this text. In which case, I'll offer a little bit more about my self and music: I love music - I don't need to wax poetic about music because we all love it, it's universal. I don't know much about music, but I do know that I love it and the more I learn about music theory and the mathematics/physics of sound the more I get drawn in. I never thought of myself as a musician and still don't - but I've started making lil loops here and there as a sort of brain exercise to think about circular motions in a conceptual manner. If you're interested in some non-sense that is mostly me just learning how to press buttons poorly feel free to listen here:

https://open.spotify.com/artist/1U9oQ2kPIAOymZLvRK4wrs?si=QUACrFUnRfmW1noSGF6O-w&dl_branch=1

Still here?

Me too.

Until Next Time,

E
